\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seismicity is frequently used to deduce the tectonics of a region.
 The study of earthquakes as a tectonic component, the seismotectonics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scholz"

\end_inset

, has grown as one of the key research areas on active tectonics, specially
 from the analysis of earthquake focal mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first focal mechanism determination methods, based on P wave's first
 motion polarities, were developed on the first half of the 20th century,
 specially in Japan where a dense seismic network were available 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "byer28,byer38,koni41,hond52,sche57"

\end_inset

.
 Since 1960 the development of the digital computer allow the numerical
 determination of fault-plane solutions with different methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "knop61,lang75,dzie81"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In parallel with the development of the modern seismology, the theory of
 Plate Tectonics changed the way geologists understand the Earth.
 Since the end of the 16th century naturalists made observations on the
 potential continental drifting; but it was in the early 20th century when
 the theory started to be formally proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tayl10,wege12,schw19,holm31"

\end_inset

.
 The relevant information acquired on the magnetic stripes on the ocean
 floor in the 60's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "hess62,vine66,lepi68,morg68"

\end_inset

, in addition to an increasing number of geological and geophysical observations
, established the Plate Tectonics as the global geodynamical paradigm on
 Earth Sciences.
 The study of earthquakes related to Plate Tectonics was developed at the
 same time establishing the basic concepts of seismotectonics and the lithospher
ic deformation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "beni54,syke67,isac68,isac69"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the 70's focal mechanisms are computed in a systematic way and global
 catalogs of focal mechanisms are available since then.
 As the amount of data increases, our knowledge on the active tectonics
 improves.
 As a consequence of the continuous increase of data available we need new
 tools to analyze it systematically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to represent focal mechanism populations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "froh92"

\end_inset

 proposed a diagram to visualize focal mechanism data as a function of the
 rupture type.
 This kind of representation is popular and widely used on seismotectonics
 to represent the focal mechanism types of the study areas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "froh97,borg01,igar01,ratc02,kita06,serp07"

\end_inset

.
 This representation is not accurate, presenting distortion problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "froh01"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kaga05"

\end_inset

 used the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kave96"

\end_inset

 projection to avoid them.
 The latter projection is used in 
\family typewriter
FMC
\family default
 by default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The focal mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

focal mechanism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used to refer to the parameters that characterize an earthquake rupture.
 A focal mechanism usually presents the characteristics of the two orthogonal
 possible rupture planes: strike, dip and rake of the slip vector over the
 plane.
 The energy released by the event, its hypocentral location and the exact
 time of occurrence are also given.
 The focal mechanism can, instead of describe the geometry of the possible
 rupture planes (6 variables), describe the characteristics of the rupture
 by means of the seismic moment tensor (SMT) or centroid moment tensor (CMT)
 (6 variables).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SMT is based in the representation of the equivalent forces on a point
 seismic source.
 In this tensor the sum of angular moments should be null, in other words,
 the SMT is a symmetric tensor on a three dimensional space (9 components)
 with 6 independent components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pmb{M}=\begin{pmatrix}M_{XX} & M_{XY} & M_{XZ}\\
M_{YX} & M_{YY} & M_{YZ}\\
M_{ZX} & M_{ZY} & M_{ZZ}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
M_{XY}=M_{YX}\nonumber \\
M_{XZ}=M_{ZX}\\
M_{YZ}=M_{ZY}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly to the strain tensor where we can define the orientation of the
 principal axes (eigenvectors) and its magnitudes (eigenvalues), the SMT
 can be defined by the orientation of its principal axes P, B and T (eigenvector
s) and its magnitudes (eigenvalues).
 The T axis describes the greatest of the eigenvalues, the P describes the
 lowest and the B the intermediate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the seismic event is generated by the slip in a fault rupture, its characteri
stics should be well described as a double couple moment tensor (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig1"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pmb{M}=\begin{bmatrix}M_{0} & 0 & 0\\
0 & -M_{0} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the scalar seismic moment.
\end_layout

